## Interaction Design Patterns to Avoid

### The Forced Click
Requiring learners to click through every item 
in a list before the Next button activates. 
Creates frustration, not engagement.

### The Obvious Answer
A scenario where one option is clearly correct 
and the others are absurd. Provides the illusion 
of practice without the substance.

### The Gotcha Question
Deliberately tricky or misleading questions 
designed to catch learners out. Tests adversarial 
reading, not job performance.

### The Wall of Text Disguised as Interaction
Click to reveal that unveils paragraphs of dense text. 
Interaction design is not a substitute for 
good information design.

### The Irrelevant Game
Gamification applied to content where engagement 
isn't the problem — or where the game mechanics 
have nothing to do with the performance objective.

### The Inaccessible Interaction
Drag and drop, timed activities, or mouse-dependent 
interactions with no accessible alternative. 
